Getting Started with Linux: Essential Commands Explained::

Date   ==> Shows the current date
Whoami ==> shows in which user u  have loggedin
pwd(print working directory)  ==> it shows in which directory u r currently in
mkdir  ==> to make directory
rmdir ==> to remove directory
touch filename.txt ==> To create an empty file
cat Filename.txt  ==> It shows the content inside the file.
cat > filename.txt ==> It will overwrite the content in the file
cat >> filename.txt ==> It will add additional content to the file
Ctrl+C  ==> to exit from cat command 
cat -n filename.txt ==> how many no of content or lines in the files
ls ==> is to list the files or directories
nano filename.txt ==> it is used to edit the content in the file . Because in cat command we cant edit the content , so for that purpose we will be using nano or vi to edit 
ctrl+o ==> to save the edit (nano)
ctrl=x ==> to exit the nano
vi filename.txt ==>it is used to edit the content in the file . Because in cat command we cant edit the content , so for that purpose we will be using nano or vi to edit
I ==> to insert the content or to write the content in VI (will change it from read mode to write or edit mode)
:w  ==> to save the edit in vi
:q ==> to quit the vi
:wq ==> to save the edit and quit vi
Echo "Content" filename.txt==> print the command in the terminal
rm filename.txt ==> to remove the specific file
